Que 9. Can you catch multiple exceptions in a single catch block in Java?How is it useful?
Ans: Yes, Java allows catching multiple exceptions in single catch block using multi-catch(|) operators.
	e.g.
		
		public class Demo{
			 public static void main(String[] args){
			 
			 try{
			 	int[] arr= {10,20,30};
			 	
			 	system.out.println(arr[4]); //ArrayIndexOutOfBound
			 	int x = 10/0;  //ArithmeticException		 
			 }
			 catch(ArithmeticException | ArrayIndexOutOfBoundException  e){
			 system.out.println( Exception handled + e);
			 }
			}
		}
	
	
***********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

Que 10. What is a custom exception and when should you use one?
Ans: Custom exceptions is an exception created by programmer to represent application specific error conditions
	Its also called a user-defined exception.
	It can created by extending Exception or RuntimeException
	
	Use a custom exceptions when:
		YOu want to clearly represent a domain-specific error.
		Built-in exceptions are not expressive enough.
		
	class InvalidAgeException extends Exception {
	public InvalidAgeException(String message) {
		super(message);
	}
}

public class CustomExceptionExample {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		try {
			try {
				checkAge(15);
			} catch (InvalidAgeException e) {
				System.out.println("Exception caught: " + e.getMessage());
			}
			checkAge(24);
		}
		catch(Exception e) {

		}
	}

	public static void checkAge(int age) throws InvalidAgeException {
		if (age < 18) {
			throw new InvalidAgeException("Age must be 18 or above.");
		}
		System.out.println("Age is valid.");
	}
}
	
***********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

	
Que 11. How does exception handling differ in Java?(e.g., multi-catch, try-with-resources)			
Ans : Exception handling is a mechanism to detect, handle and recover the runtime error.
		Multi-catch:
			It catches the multiple exception in one catch block using (|) operators.
			
			try{
			int[] arr = {1,2};
			system.out.println(arr[5]/0);
			}catch(ArithmeticException | ArrayIndexOutOfBound e){
			system.out.pritln(Exception handled);
			}
			
		try-with-resources:
			It is exception handling mechnasim that ensures that resources (like file streams, database connection) are automatically closed after they are used.
			
			try(FileReader fr = new FileReader(data.txt)){
			 system.out.println(file opened);
			 }
			 
